Patch Set 7:

Forgot to add that I'm in favor of this change.  With the current design of the image import refactor workflow, we need to restrict the number of images an end-user can create or else someone could DOS the system by filling up the database with junk images for which they had no intention of providing image data for.

Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

(2 comments)

This patch should probably end up looking more like the storage equivalent:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/37993/

Although, it has to be said that that patch makes the v1 API talk directly to the database -- bypassing the registry -- which surprises me a bit.

It also has some weird side effects: https://bugs.launchpad.net/glance/+bug/1516706


> With the current design of the image import refactor workflow, we need to restrict the number of images an end-user can create or else someone could DOS the system by filling up the database with junk images for which they had no intention of providing image data for.

For import do we want to restrict the total number or just enforce 'sane' usage?
We could potenailly do something like allow N images to be in either 'queued'/'saving'/'killed' state (ie not 'active'), before forcing someone to clean up by preventing creation of new images?

Patch Set 7:

I'm not a db person, but I wonder if it would be possible to have a per-tenant counter in the db. It would be incremented (as part of a transaction) when image records are created and decremented when they are deleted.

Patch Set 7:

(6 comments)

Agree with Stuart. I prefer to achieve it with db like Nova quota does. But I'm not sure what the Glance team think. As the storage quota has been achieved with config option, I did the same here. Maybe we need have a discussion on weekly meeting? I'll continue work on this patch before we have a conclusion.

Patch Set 7:

@Stuart, I guess the reason why v1 call db directly is to keep the  same with v2. If we do like v2. We can change the value in glance-api.conf only. Otherwise, v1's config option is in glance-registry.conf and v2s' in glance-api.conf, that maybe confuse users.
